{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.24,0.03,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68091"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9663"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53548"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4470"},{"type":"tags","id":"4671"},{"type":"tags","id":"11153"},{"type":"tags","id":"11993"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12958"},{"type":"tags","id":"12962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68091"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the labour ward in active labour at 39 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She is a refugee who arrived in Australia three months ago and has had minimal antenatal care. She speaks limited English and a telephone interpreter is used. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with contractions every three minutes. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. On perineal examination, there is absence of the clitoris and labia minora, with intact labia majora. The vaginal introitus is patent.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these examination findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 1 female genital mutilation","Type 4 female genital mutilation","Type 3 female genital mutilation","Congenital labial adhesions","Type 2 female genital mutilation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with examination findings consistent with female genital mutilation (FGM), specifically Type 2. The World Health Organization classifies FGM into four main types based on the extent of tissue removal and alteration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 female genital mutilation\u003C/strong\u003E involves partial or total removal of the clitoral glans and/or clitoral hood only. This is less extensive than what is described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 female genital mutilation\u003C/strong\u003E involves partial or total removal of the clitoris and labia minora, without removal of the labia majora. This matches the examination findings in this case, where the clitoris and labia minora are absent but the labia majora remain intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 3 female genital mutilation\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as infibulation, involves narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal by cutting and repositioning the labia minora or labia majora. This patient\u0027s vaginal introitus is described as patent, ruling out type 3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 4 female genital mutilation\u003C/strong\u003E includes all other harmful procedures to female genitalia for non-medical purposes, such as pricking, piercing, incising, scraping, or cauterising. This type does not typically involve tissue removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital labial adhesions\u003C/strong\u003E typically present as fusion of the labia minora in the midline, creating a thin, translucent membrane. This would not explain the absence of clitoral tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecognition of FGM during pregnancy is crucial as it may impact labour and delivery. Women with FGM are at increased risk of prolonged labour, obstetric tears, postpartum haemorrhage, and need for caesarean section. They should receive specialist multidisciplinary care including psychological support.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Female genital mutilation type 2 involves partial or total removal of the clitoris and labia minora, without removal of the labia majora.","FGM increases risks of obstetric complications including obstructed labour, perineal tears, and postpartum haemorrhage.","Antenatal identification of FGM is crucial for birth planning and specialist involvement."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Female genital mutilation (FGM) [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Female-Genital-Mutilation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53548"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53548"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T09:44:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-